5.2 Earth-Based Prototype (AWR-E1)

Specifications

· Scale: 1:1 mass and dimensions
· Gravity Compensation: Active system for Mars-equivalent loading
· Test Environments:
  · Dust chamber (Mars pressure, CO₂ atmosphere)
  · Thermal vacuum chamber (-130°C to +70°C)
  · Vibration table (launch simulation)
  · Mars yard (rocky terrain, slopes, obstacles)

Test Campaigns

1. Mobility: 1,000 km of walking over varied terrain
2. Durability: 100,000 joint cycles under maximum load
3. Autonomy: 1,000 hours of unsupervised operation
4. Tools: 10,000 tool swaps with performance verification

5.3 Field Testing Locations

1. Atacama Desert, Chile: Mars-analog dust and aridity
2. Devon Island, Canada: Geological analog, cold environment
3. Mauna Ulu, Hawaii: Volcanic terrain, isolation testing
4. Woomera, Australia: Remote operations, large scale

5.4 Flight Qualification

Launch Environment

· Vibration: 14.1 Grms overall (20-2000 Hz)
· Acoustic: 146 dB overall sound pressure level
· Shock: 3,000 G peak (pyro devices)
· Acceleration: 6.5 G axial, 2.5 G lateral

Space Environment

· Vacuum: 10⁻⁶ Torr operational
· Temperature: -150°C to +125°C survival
· Radiation: 50 krad(Si) mission dose
· Micrometeoroids: 0.5mm @ 10 km/s protection

Mars Entry, Descent, and Landing (EDL)

· Heatshield: 1,700°C peak temperature
· Deceleration: 12 G peak
· Landing: 2 m/s vertical, 1 m/s horizontal
· Touchdown Slope: Up to 15° from horizontal

